Yeah — you’re not crazy to think that. What you’re describing is basically real-time generative direction, and the trajectory of video models is clearly heading that way. 🚀

Right now systems like Sora already do something close to this but in batch mode:
	1.	You prompt a scene
	2.	The model renders a clip
	3.	You revise the prompt
	4.	Generate again

But the next step is obvious: closing the loop so the generation runs continuously while you steer it.

Think of it like three stages of evolution:

1. Batch Generation (today)
	•	Prompt → generate full clip
	•	Edit prompt → regenerate
	•	Similar to rendering frames offline

2. Iterative Direction (near term)
	•	Scene persists
	•	You change parameters live:
	•	camera angle
	•	character movement
	•	lighting
	•	dialogue
	•	Model updates the scene between frames

3. Real-Time Simulation (what you’re talking about)
	•	The world keeps running
	•	You give director commands in real time
	•	AI fills the gaps between instructions

It becomes closer to:
	•	film directing
	•	game engine control
	•	simulation steering

Like combining:
	•	Sora
	•	Unreal Engine
	•	Unity

…but the assets generate themselves on the fly.

